<div class="prose">

<p>The Hydrologist is <strong>Unit 5's broad-scope water-systems partner</strong>. It helps you reason about water cycles, residence times, watersheds, aquifers, and water quality — and translate that physical hydrology into the specific dynamics of your chosen water-rights case (Cauvery, Indus, Colorado, Nile, Mekong, Aral, Cooum, Bangalore). Patient, technically precise, policy-aware. Holds a clear line: it helps with the science underneath the dispute, not the advocacy on top of it. That's <em>your</em> job.</p>

{% include "partials/partner-launch.njk" %}

<h2>Overview — why this partner is uniquely valuable</h2>
<p>Water disputes are mis-framed when you skip the hydrology. The Cauvery dispute isn't fundamentally about Tamil Nadu vs. Karnataka — it's about a finite, monsoon-driven, partially-overdrawn river system on top of multiple depleting aquifers, with residence times that mean some allocations can be renegotiated and others can't. The Hydrologist makes that structure visible. It's particularly useful for the Position Paper's <strong>Background</strong> section (where you frame the dispute hydrologically for a reader who doesn't already know the basin) and for the Stakeholders Map's <strong>Evidence They Cite</strong> column (different stakeholders cite different evidence because different hydrological facts matter for different positions).</p>
<p>One critical distinction the partner holds the line on: <strong>physical scarcity vs. economic scarcity</strong>. Most "water shortage" framing collapses the two, and the collapse matters because the solutions are different (more reservoirs vs. better institutions). The Hydrologist will ask you which kind of scarcity your case actually has.</p>

<h2>Pairs with</h2>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">The Source Evaluator</a></strong> — when you're applying OPVL to government reports, tribunal documents, NGO statements, news pieces, or AI summaries on your case. The Hydrologist helps you reason about <em>what</em> a source is claiming about the water system; the Source Evaluator helps you reason about <em>how much to trust</em> the source.</p>
<p><strong><a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">The Stakeholder Voice</a></strong> — different roles, complementary. The Hydrologist handles the underlying water-systems science; the Stakeholder Voice handles the perspective-taking on top of it. If you ask the Hydrologist "who's right in this dispute?" it'll redirect you to the Stakeholder Voice + your own analytic work.</p>

